So, for `I ⊆ V(G, M)` and `V(G, M) ⊆ V(G)`, we automatically have `I ⊆ V(G)`. The goal is essentially to prove that `V(G, M) ⊆ V(G)` for any matching `M`, which is true because all edges in `M` are in `G`.

